text:
Black Friday 2019: Know When It Will Be And Check Out Average Discounts
21% of Brazilian business and service entrepreneurs must participate in promotions
06 Nov 2019, 13:04 by From THE PEOPLE Online | Northeast Network
Increasingly part of the national retail calendar of commemorative dates, Black Friday 2019 will take place exactly on Friday, November 29th. The tradition, which began in the United States, arrived in Brazil in 2010 and left only online to physical stores. Some companies, besides the day itself, take advantage of the whole month to offer promotions. This year this will be the main strategy and discounts will average 24%.
The data was collected by a survey of the National Confederation of Shopkeepers (CNDL) and the Credit Protection Service (SPC Brazil). In the survey, 21% of Brazilian business and service entrepreneurs are expected to participate in Black Friday 2019 promotions. They are hopeful about the date and more than a third believe the results will be higher than last year.
Although it is close to Christmas, 54% think Black Friday shopping does not affect the Christmas season. SPC Brazil explains that these advance purchases are focused on more individual products for the home, but already at Christmas the goal is to give friends and family. With discounts, it's important to be aware and not fall for scams or fraudulent promotions.
15 tips for those looking to shop at Black Friday
1. Check the prices charged before the Black Friday day, through the websites of the companies that will attend the event. This avoids the risk of falling for fraudulent promotions;
2. Taking a print or photo of the desired product prices week by week until the day of the offers is indicated;
3. Check the delivery time of the goods at home, which must be registered in the invoice or receipt. According to Claudia Buhamra, UFC marketing professor, it is also important to warn about the conditions of delivery of the product, as well as the services (if the product needs to be assembled, for example);
4. Pay attention to exchange and return policies, which may be changed by stores. This is the "moment of truth", according to Claudia. "At the time of purchase, everything is very easy, everyone wants to sell, everyone has the best product, everyone has the best offer. It's good to check the reliability of the product brand and the retail brand seller."
5. Carefully analyze the footnotes and any different delivery conditions that the store may apply during this period;
6. Examine the goods and only sign the proof of receipt after confirmation of the conditions of the product (any irregularity must be justified and the responsible company must solve the problem);
7. Search the Consumer Protection Bodies, the consumer.gov.br platform and Google for any references to the site.
8. Assess the credibility of the selling source. If the brand of the product is of quality, it is reliable, if the store where the purchase is being made has a recognized brand to provide customer service after the purchase.
9. Breathe, reflect and walk around the stores calmly. "Evaluate products, evaluate brands, evaluate the quality of the product itself, talk to credible reference sources. Search the life of that supplier, that manufacturer or that retailer on social networks," warns the expert.


Specifically for internet purchases:


10. Prior to purchase, check the reliability of the store, make sure the site contains the supplier's corporate name, CNPJ, address, and contact channels, because if a problem occurs, locating the business will be critical to the solution;
11. Save the emails exchanged with the supplier, which are proof in case of exchanges or non-receipt of the product;
12. Prefer reputable suppliers in the market;
13. In the case of imported products purchased in Brazil, they follow the same rules as nationals provided they are from legalized establishments;
14. Install antivirus programs and the firewall. These software prevent the transmission and / or reception of harmful or unauthorized access. Always keep them updated on your computer;
15. Try not to shop online at internet cafes, cyber cafes or public computers as they may not be adequately protected.
"The biggest risk is anxiety," Black Friday expert warns
Assess the credibility of the selling source. This is the first and main tip that the professor of marketing at the Federal University of Ceará (UFC), Claudia Buhamra, gives to those who want to buy at Black Friday. The festival of discounts takes place on November 29, on a Friday (as the name suggests in English). On the day, the expectation is that the prices of market products, from electronics to personal consumer goods, will be lower.
“If the brand of the product is of quality, it is reliable. If the store where the purchase is being made has a recognized brand in order to provide customer service especially after the purchase, ”continues Claudia. This is the well-known "time of truth," as the teacher calls it.

